# Phase 3: Performance Telemetry & Fixes

## Problem Analysis (The 1 FPS Issue)
While we replaced thousands of React `CuboidCollider` components with a single `<InstancedRigidBodies>` wrapper, Rapier is *still* simulating thousands of individual physical cube colliders per chunk under the hood. Furthermore, making [GlitchMaterial](file:///c:/AppDev/The_Glitch_In_the_Goblet_ARPG/src/components/shaders/GlitchMaterial.tsx#13-88) transparent introduces severe GPU overdraw and depth-sorting penalties when applied to thousands of instances.

## 1. Agentic Performance Testing Pipeline
To allow the AI to autonomously benchmark and diagnose the app, we will build a headless-compatible telemetry pipeline:

### A. The Telemetry System (Frontend)
1.  **React Profiler Integration:** Wrap critical components ([Chunk](file:///c:/AppDev/The_Glitch_In_the_Goblet_ARPG/src/components/world/Chunk.tsx#15-106), [World](file:///c:/AppDev/The_Glitch_In_the_Goblet_ARPG/src/components/game/World.tsx#11-72), [Player](file:///c:/AppDev/The_Glitch_In_the_Goblet_ARPG/src/components/game/Player.tsx#12-124)) in React's `<Profiler>` API.
2.  **FPS & Memory Hooks:** Create a custom `useTelemetry` hook that samples `useFrame` delta times to calculate average FPS and frame drops.
3.  **Data Export:** Instead of just logging to the console (which can be hard for an agent to parse continuously), the telemetry system will batch metrics every 5 seconds and `POST` them to a simple local API endpoint, or alternatively, render a hidden JSON `<div>` in the DOM containing the latest stats.

### B. The Automated Profiler (Agent Side)
1.  Since the agent has access to a `browser_subagent`, the agent can autonomously spin up a headless browser session navigating to `http://localhost:5173`.
2.  The subagent will be instructed to read the hidden Telemetry DOM node or intercept console logs.
3.  The subagent reports the exact FPS, render times, and physics times back to the main agent for analysis.

## 2. Immediate Performance Fixes
Before we run the profiler, there are two distinct bottlenecks we need to fix:

### A. Physics: Greedy Meshing for Colliders
Instead of generating 4,000 1x1x1 colliders per chunk, we will implement a basic 1D or 2D Greedy Meshing algorithm.
*   The algorithm will scan the chunk data and merge adjacent solid blocks along the X or Z axis into large rectangles.
*   A single chunk might drop from 4,096 colliders down to ~200, drastically freeing up the CPU.
*   *Note: We only do this for the physics colliders. The visuals can remain a single `InstancedMesh` of 1x1x1 cubes since the GPU handles instancing efficiently, provided transparency is turned off.*

### B. Rendering: Opaque Materials
*   Remove `transparent=true` from the base terrain [GlitchMaterial](file:///c:/AppDev/The_Glitch_In_the_Goblet_ARPG/src/components/shaders/GlitchMaterial.tsx#13-88). Transparent instanced meshes destroy fill-rate.
*   If we need camera dithering/fading, we should use a `customDepthMaterial` or completely avoid transparency unless strictly necessary.

## Proposed Implementation Steps
1. [MODIFY] [src/components/world/Chunk.tsx](file:///c:/AppDev/The_Glitch_In_the_Goblet_ARPG/src/components/world/Chunk.tsx) - Implement Greedy Meshing for the Rapier bounding boxes. Remove transparency from [GlitchMaterial](file:///c:/AppDev/The_Glitch_In_the_Goblet_ARPG/src/components/shaders/GlitchMaterial.tsx#13-88).
2. [NEW] `src/utils/telemetry.ts` - Create the data aggregator.
3. [NEW] `src/components/core/TelemetryProvider.tsx` - Inject React `<Profiler>` and the `useFrame` FPS counter.
4. [MODIFY] [src/App.tsx](file:///c:/AppDev/The_Glitch_In_the_Goblet_ARPG/src/App.tsx) - Wrap the app in the TelemetryProvider to expose DOM metrics.
